Computation is performed via different sets of lasers interacting with the atoms in the AOD/SLM arrays.
When an atom is highly excited, its outermost electron
occupies a Rydberg state, meaning it has an enlarged
orbit that allows interactions with nearby atoms.
Local Rydberg lasers can be used to excite individual atoms
Rydberg blockade effect: If one atom is in a Rydberg state, neighboring atoms within a certain radius cannot be
similarly excited if they are not involved in a gate with that atom
❌ restricts parallelism: any atoms in the blockade radius cannot themselves perform multi-qubit gates
(though they can still perform single-atom Raman transitions).
This blockade radius is typically 2.5× the interaction radius
2-qubit gate running on Q0-Q1 => Q2 is blocked
(2-qubit gate cannot run simultaneously in Q2-Q3, Q2-Q4)
Both one-qubit U3 gates and two-qubit CZ gates can
be executed in parallel on different qubits in the system

The grid of atoms trapped in the SLM and AOD are together called the qubit topology or layout.
The topology defines how the qubits are positioned in the hardware.

optimize to achieve the best placement of atoms for upcoming operations

✅ placing only one atom per AOD row/column pair
1. rows and columns cross over each other with significantly lower frequency
=> localizes each atom close to other atoms it interacts with
2. No other atoms have to move in tandem
=> increases the average number of gates execute in parallel
(一个正在与其它原子发生相互作用的原子不会因为同行/列的原子的移动而被移出相互作用半径从而受到影响)
3. less obstruction from the atoms’ minimum separation distance constraint
=> atom collision is also less frequent
(如果一个AOD原子挡了另一个AOD原子的路, 可以将它移开)
4. make it easier to parallelize different operations
❌ place all atoms in either the SLM or AOD
1. all SLM: SWAPs would be the only option for bringing atoms closer
2. all AOD: separation distance and AOD row/column overlap constraints↑
=> a large number of SWAP operations and trap changes would be required
how to select qubits to place in the AOD while maintaining one qubit per AOD row/column
heuristic algorithm
1. assign weight to each AOD atoms
2. The set of highest-weight qubits are placed in the AOD as close to their initial locations as possible
3. recursively adjust until no shared row/column

Experiment
simulator that emulates the hardware characteristics of real neutral atom testbed systems
QuEra Aquila does not yet support a programmable AOD
input: circuit in QASM format
1. executes Graphine to optimize qubit placement using dual annealing
-> returning coordinates in a [0,1] range for each qubit
2. maps qubits to atoms based on the simulation size
3. obtains an ideal Rydberg interaction distance from Graphine
4. Atoms are initially placed in the SLM object, with SLM traps represented as
an array of fixed site coordinates
5. Selected atoms are then ”moved” into AOD traps, chosen by an algorithm
iterating through all qubits in the input circuit
If AOD atoms block a move, they are recursively
moved, with a hard limit of 80 recursive iterations
to prevent infinite loops.
Failed moves are resolved using trap changes.
Evaluation Metrics:
1. CZ Gate Count
2. Probability of Success
3. Circuit Runtime
4. Total Execution Time(8000 logical shots)
